Summary¶

The goal of this assignment is to find a timeseries forecasting model that predicts online retail sales profits over a prediction horizon of three months. The predictions need to be made based on a representative sample of sales from the past year. The assignment is split into three main parts: descriptive analysis, models development and model selection.

As part of the descriptive analysis the profit is calculated as the product of quantity and unit price. It is then analyzed against several variables such as by month, weekday and country. Next, the stationarity of the data is checked with the the Dickey-Fuller test and the Mann-Kendall test. The Mann-Kendall test reveals that there is an increasing trend over the periods of one week, one month and three months. It is not possible to investigate if there is a yearly seasonality since the data available only goes back on year. In preparation for the model building the lags are analyzed in terms of autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation. Even though the weekly seasonality is taken into consideration it is not possible to perform additive decomposition of the time series. Besides, multiplicative decomposition cannot be applied since there are some negative values and missing values in the dataset.

To make the predictions five different types of models are built, SARIMAX, Auto ARIMA, Prophet, XGBoost and KNN. The models are evaluated based on the mean absolute error, the root mean squared error and the mean absolute percentage error. After finetuning some hyperparameters the XGBoost model turns out to be the best-performing model considering all three metrics. To make the final forecast a pipeline including a scaler, a deseasonalizer and the hampel filter is set up based on this XGBoost model.

A function is defined to perform Dickey fuller test to check for stationarity:

In [ ]:
def dickey_fuller(x):
    result=adfuller(x)
    print('ADF Statistic:', result[0])
    print('p-value:', result[1])
    print('Critical Values:', result[4])
    if result[1] <= 0.05:
        print("Reject the null hypothesis. Time series is stationary.")
    else:
        print("Fail to reject the null hypothesis. Time series is non-stationary.")

Another function is defined for the Mann-Kendall test to see if results regarding stationarity are the same as shown by the dickey fuller test

In [ ]:
def check_trend(time_series, alpha=0.05):
    result = mk.original_test(time_series, alpha=alpha)
    return result

df_ar.loc[df_ar['Date']<= '2023-09-25', 'type'] = 'train'

df_ar.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

Based on the autocorrelation and partial autocorrelation the parameters for the ARIMAX model will be set as follows:

  • p=7 - partial autocorrelation values become statistically irrelevant after 7 lags
  • q=3 - autocorrelation values become statistically irrelevant after 3 lags
  • d=1 - one lag is needed to make time series stationary

Seasonal order: none since it is difficult to interpret if there really is seasonality in the data since the data is only available for one year. So far in the data that is showing there does not seem to be periodicity.

def pred(x):
    new_dates_test = pd.date_range('2023-12-10', freq = 'D', periods=90)
    df_new = df_ar.copy()
    df_pred = pd.DataFrame(pd.to_datetime(new_dates_test))
    df_pred.columns = ['Date']
    df_pred['Profit'] = np.nan
    df_pred.rename_axis(None, inplace=True)
    df_pred.set_index('Date', inplace=True)
    df_pred = df_pred.sort_index(ascending=True)
    df_pred.index.freq = 'D'
    df_now_after = pd.concat([df_new,df_pred])
    df_now_after['Predictions'] = x.predict(start='2022-12-01',end='2024-03-09') # total days including out-sample
    ax = px.line(df_now_after, x=df_now_after.index, y = ['Profit','Predictions'],   template = 'plotly_white')
    return ax

To evaluate the models several metrics will be calculated. Aside from the common root mean squared error the mean absolute error and the mean absolute percentage error are taken into account.

In [ ]:
def metrics(result):
    df_res = df_ar.copy()
    df_res['Profit_pred'] = np.concatenate([result.predict(start=0,end=299), result.predict(start=300, end=373)])
    mae = mean_absolute_error(df_res[df_res['type'] == 'test']['Profit'], df_res[df_res['type'] == 'test']['Profit_pred']).round(2)
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(df_res[df_res['type'] == 'test']['Profit'], df_res[df_res['type'] == 'test']['Profit_pred']).round(2)
    mse = mean_squared_error(df_res[df_res['type'] == 'test']['Profit'], df_res[df_res['type'] == 'test']['Profit_pred']).round(2)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
    return mae, mape, rmse

2.2) Auto ARIMA¶

2.2.1) Model building¶

In order to optimize the ARIMA model auto arima will be run. The parameters are set as follows:

  • p=5-9 - add an upper and lower threshold to the previously selected p = 7
  • q=1-5 - add an upper and lower threshold to the previously selected q = 3
  • d=0-2 - add an upper and lower threshold to the previously selected d = 1
  • sesaonality = True

2.3) Prophet¶

2.3.1) Model building¶

Since this model has the option to include Sundays and holidays it will be trained with this information from the beginning. We create a dataframe to be used for forecasts with prophet and include info on whether the data belongs to the train or test set and if the weekday is a sunday

In [ ]:

df5_prophet.loc[df5_prophet.Weekday ==6, 'Weekday'] = 1

df5_prophet['ds'] = df5_prophet.index
df5_prophet.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=False)

df5_prophet.loc[df5_prophet['ds']> '2023-09-25', 'type'] = 'test'

Parameters
----------
values : pd.Index, pd.TimedeltaIndex, np.array, list, pd.Timedelta, or int
    Values of forecasting horizon
is_relative : bool, optional (default=None)
    - If True, a relative ForecastingHorizon is created:

    - If False, an absolute ForecastingHorizon is created:

    object carrying frequency information on values
    ignored unless values is without inferable freq

3.2) Model Selection and final forecast¶

The idea is to use the secong XGBoost model as part of a pipeline, which includes a scaler, aHampel filter to soften outliers and a deseasonalizer.

In [ ]:
class HampelFilter(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, window_size=3, n_sigmas=3):
        self.window_size = window_size
        self.n_sigmas = n_sigmas

    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self

    def transform(self, X):
#ensure X is a DataFrame
        if not isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame):
            X = pd.DataFrame(X)

        for col in X.columns:
#calculate rolling median and standard deviation
            rolling_median = X[col].rolling(window=self.window_size, center=True).median()
            rolling_std = X[col].rolling(window=self.window_size, center=True).std()

#identify outliers
            outliers = (np.abs(X[col] - rolling_median) > self.n_sigmas * rolling_std)

#replace outliers with rolling median
            X[col][outliers] = rolling_median[outliers]

        return X

To fit the pipeline the training data and test data must not contain any null values. Therefore, the same training data and test data that were used to train the KNN model will be used here. The imputed training data is transformed into a dataframe:

Conclusion: At the end it is possible to optimize the error metrics of the XGBoost model by creating a pipeline. However, according to the MAE the actual values still deviate on average by 4560 GBP from the predictions made by the model. In the real world the model would need to be optimized even more to create trustworthy predictions for the business. As mentioned in the Descriptive Analysis it would be great to have more data available to able to compare the data year over year. Knowing whether or not there is yearly seasonality could possibly improve the model further.
